🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐂𝐎𝐑𝐑𝐄𝐂𝐓 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐂𝐈𝐀𝐓𝐈𝐂𝐀! [nerve floss] 🚨 by @lustrengththerapy 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Sciatica refers to pain that radiates along the sciatic nerve (travels from the lower back through the back of your hips and into the leg).

While there are several different causes of sciatica such as a herniation, nerve impingement and muscular imbalances, promoting movement along that nerve can help minimize your symptoms and provide temporary relief. By doing so, it will also give you a window of opportunity to perform other rehab exercises to help with your sciatica.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗘𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗡𝗘𝗥𝗩𝗘 𝗙𝗟𝗢𝗦𝗦:
Sit on a chair or bench with your legs at 90 degrees. Extend one leg forward with the toes pointed towards yourself and extend the head backwards. Flex the same side knee while tucking the chin and looking downwards.

2️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗡𝗘𝗥𝗩𝗘 𝗙𝗟𝗢𝗦𝗦:
Stand with one leg elevated on a bench or chair. Point the toes forward while simultaneously hinging the hips backwards. Pull the toes up towards the ceiling while straightening out the back and hips and repeat.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗨𝗣𝗜𝗡𝗘 𝗡𝗘𝗥𝗩𝗘 𝗙𝗟𝗢𝗦𝗦:
Lay face up on the ground with both legs bent to roughly 45 degrees. Pull one knee up towards the chest and reinforced with both hands behind the hamstrings. Pull the toes up and extend the knee towards the ceiling. Pull the knee back down to the starting position.

⁉️ Do you have pain in the side of the low back?
➖➖➖➖➖ 
➡️ TAG a Friend Who Would Like This 😉👇.
➡️ If you like it pls support with ❤️ 😉👇
➖➖➖➖➖
➖➖➖➖➖⠀
🎯 Many times the quadratus lumborum, or the "QL", can contribute to pain in this area, as palpating this deep muscle can be very sensitive in some individuals
-
📌 This muscle connects from the top/back of the pelvis (iliac crest) to the 12th rib (the lowest one), as well as the transverse processes of the lumbar spine vertebrae (side projections of the low back bones)
-
🤸🏻 Its function is to extend (arch backward) and side bend the spine and can also act as a stabilizer, resisting side bending into the opposite direction as well as spinal flexion (forward bending)
-
🚨 If you have pain in this region, a combination of stretching and strengthening is often helpful
-
🎥 Here are some exercises that may help:
-
1️⃣ Spinal Side Bending at Door
2️⃣ Supine Lumbar Rotation
3️⃣ Sidelying Lumbar Rotation
4️⃣ Single Leg Bridge
5️⃣ Side Plank
6️⃣ Suitcase Carries
-
🚨 Remember, these are simply examples of exercises that MAY help. If you need a specific exercise program tailored to your specific situation, you should schedule a consult with the physical therapist you trust!
-
🙏🏼 I hope that was helpful!

⁉️ Want to build strong lats?
➖➖➖➖➖ 
❤️ TAG or SHARE this post with someone in quarantine who needs these bodyweight triceps exercises
➡️ If you like it pls support with ❤️ 😉👇
➖➖➖➖➖

➖➖➖➖➖⠀
🎥 Here I show just 9 examples of exercises you can use to target this large muscle group 💪🏼
-
📊 Set and rep range will depend on individual goals, but a good start would be 3-5 sets of 6-12 reps, 2-3x/week
-
🤓 Quick Functional Anatomy Lesson:
-
The lats connect to the following:
-
🔹 Origin: Posterior third of crest of ilium (top and back of the pelvis), Spinous processes of vertebrae T7-T12 (middle spine), thoracolumbar fascia, ribs 9-12, and in some cases the inferior angle of scapula (shoulder blade)
-
🔹 Insertion: Intertubercular sulcus of the humerus (the front part of your shoulder), between pectoralis major and teres major muscles
-
🔹 Innervation: Thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8)
-
🔹 Action: shoulder extension, adduction, internal rotation (bringing the arm backward, inward across the body, and rotating the arm inward), lumbar extension, and can assist with respiration and trunk stability
-
🏋🏻 Exercise variations that work the lats well include rowing/pulling variations and those where a weight is pulled from a more overhead position of the shoulder to downward and behind the body
-
🙏🏼 I hope this was helpful!

*BRO-SPLIT VS SCIENCE* 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Alright, I figured it's been a little bit since I've posted split content so what a better day to share this awesome posts that I agree with by Oakley O'Day!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
So let me open up with a disclaimer that the bro-split is not necessarily bad.  I still remember my old log books from tracked bro splits that I have til this day.  For the most part I fell into the same trap that most everyday fitness enthusiast find in magazines by people that were on super creatine (aka enhancers etc) and were growing mad with crazy results from this type of style of workout.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
BUT as naturals, time and time again studies have shown that in order to benefit efficiently for muscle growth that hitting the muscle groups multiple times a week is the most efficient way of putting on muscle.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
What you have here is a 6 day split where each muscle group is getting hit multiple times a week.  For most this is a lot of volume so keep that in mind as you could use other splits to hit the muscle groups frequently only in less days.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This example has abs/core getting hit on a separate day as many of you know that I only hit abs directly twice a week on lower days with hanging leg raises but feel free to add any core or ab exercises you like to these types of programs.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Hope that helps!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If you made it this far please comment below "SCIENCE" as it helps me to see that I'm making a difference in your fitness goals. As always have a great day
